on and grandson, both named Edward were professors of divinity at Harvard."],"variants":[{"name":"Wiglesworth","meanings":["English: variant of   Wigglesworth  ."]},{"name":"Wrigglesworth","meanings":["English: habitational name from Woodlesford in Oulton (Yorkshire). The placename derives from Old English <i>wrīdels</i> ‘thicket’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’. There has been much confusion with   Wigglesworth  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Walter Wigglesworth married Mrs Walter Wigglesworth before 1312, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in May 1366."},"et":{"–May 1366":"–mai 1366","–Female":"Surnud","1312–Female":"1312–Surnud","–1366":"–1366","before 1312":"enne 1312","1312":"1312","1366":"1366","May 1366":"mai 1366","about 1312":"umbes 1312","England":"England","Barforth Hall, Yorkshire, England":"Barforth Hall, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"–May 1366":"–toukokuu 1366","–Female":"Kuollut","1312–Female":"1312–Kuollut","–1366":"–1366","before 1312":"ennen vuotta 1312","1312":"1312","1366":"1366","May 1366":"toukokuu 1366","about 1312":"noin 1312","England":"England","Barforth Hall, Yorkshire, England":"Barforth Hall, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"–May 1366":"–mai 1366","–Female":"Décédée","1312–Female":"1312–Décédée","–1366":"–1366","before 1312":"avant 1312","1312":"1312","1366":"1366","May 13